    <h3>The sheaf coboundary: prediction error, algebraically</h3>

    <p>
      <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2511.11092">Seely (2025)</a> constructs a
      cellular sheaf over a computational graph. The coboundary operator
      δ⁰: C⁰ → C¹ maps activations (0-cochains) to prediction errors (1-cochains):
    </p>

    <p style="text-align: center; font-family: ui-monospace, monospace;">
      (δ⁰s)<sub>e</sub> = s<sub>v</sub> − W<sub>e</sub> s<sub>u</sub>
    </p>

    <p>
      This has the same algebraic form as motion-compensated subtraction: current
      frame minus predicted frame. The predictive-coding energy is
      E = ½‖δ⁰s‖², and inference is gradient descent under the sheaf Laplacian.
    </p>

    <p>
      With clamped inputs and outputs (known source, known target), the Hodge
      decomposition splits the forcing vector into a removable component
      (in im D; better encoder choices can eliminate it) and an irreducible
      component (in ker Dᵀ; no choice of activations can remove it).
      The irreducible part lives in H¹, the first cohomology group.
    </p>

    <h3>Temporal spanner: compressing for edge count</h3>

    <p>
      A temporal α-spanner removes edges while keeping journey distances
      within a multiplicative stretch factor α. The objective is fewer edges,
      not fewer bits: no encoding is specified, no bit budget given.
    </p>

    <Repl client:visible initialCode={`class TemporalGraph:
    def __init__(self):
        self.edges = []

    def add_edge(self, u, v, t):
        self.edges.append((u, v, t))

    def journey_duration(self, start, end):
        arrival = {start: 0}
        for u, v, t in sorted(self.edges, key=lambda e: e[2]):
            if u in arrival and t >= arrival[u]:
                new_arrival = t + 1
                if v not in arrival or new_arrival < arrival[v]:
                    arrival[v] = new_arrival
        return arrival.get(end, float('inf'))

    def temporal_spanner(self, alpha):
        kept = []
        removed = []
        test_edges = sorted(self.edges, key=lambda e: -e[2])
        current = list(self.edges)

        for edge in test_edges:
            trial = [e for e in current if e != edge]
            trial_g = TemporalGraph()
            for e in trial:
                trial_g.add_edge(*e)
            full_g = TemporalGraph()
            for e in current:
                full_g.add_edge(*e)

            nodes = set()
            for u, v, t in current:
                nodes.add(u)
                nodes.add(v)

            ok = True
            for s in nodes:
                for d in nodes:
                    if s == d:
                        continue
                    orig = full_g.journey_duration(s, d)
                    new = trial_g.journey_duration(s, d)
                    if orig < float('inf') and new > alpha * orig:
                        ok = False
                        break
                if not ok:
                    break

            if ok:
                removed.append(edge)
                current = trial
            else:
                kept.append(edge)

        return sorted(kept, key=lambda e: e[2]), removed

g = TemporalGraph()
g.add_edge("A", "B", 1)
g.add_edge("A", "C", 1)
g.add_edge("B", "D", 2)
g.add_edge("C", "D", 3)
g.add_edge("B", "C", 2)
g.add_edge("A", "D", 4)

print(f"Original: {len(g.edges)} edges")
kept, removed = g.temporal_spanner(2.0)
print(f"Spanner (α=2.0): {len(kept)} kept, {len(removed)} removed")
print("Kept:")
for e in kept:
    print(f"  {e[0]}→{e[1]} @ t={e[2]}")

spanner_g = TemporalGraph()
for e in kept:
    spanner_g.add_edge(*e)

nodes = ["A", "B", "C", "D"]
print("\\nJourney durations (original → spanner):")
for s in nodes:
    for d in nodes:
        if s != d:
            orig = g.journey_duration(s, d)
            new = spanner_g.journey_duration(s, d)
            o = str(orig) if orig < float('inf') else "∞"
            n = str(new) if new < float('inf') else "∞"
            st = f" (×{new/orig:.1f})" if orig < float('inf') and new < float('inf') else ""
            print(f"  {s}→{d}: {o} → {n}{st}")`} />

    <h3>The invariance boundary</h3>

    <p>
      The <a href="https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9792072/">temporal
      state machines</a> paper establishes an invariance constraint for pure race
      logic: any function must satisfy f(t₁+δ,...,tₙ+δ) = f(t₁,...,tₙ)+δ.
      Compositions that break this symmetry require memory (state). Tropical
      multiplication — adding two time codes — cannot be done in a single
      stateless pass.
    </p>

    <p>
      This draws a line between stateless temporal composition and stateful
      computation that requires buffering. The two-phase protocol (store the
      wavefront, then apply it) echoes the I-frame/P-frame cycle: write a
      checkpoint, then compute deltas. That analogy is ours, not the paper's.
    </p>

    <h3>The gaps</h3>

    <p>
      The spanner compresses by counting edges. The codec compresses by counting
      bits. The sheaf separates removable from irreducible error but lacks
      temporal dynamics or a rate constraint. Each field has exactly what the
      others are missing. The <a href="/reading/temporal-compression/ch-04/">next
      chapter</a> lays out the open problems.
    </p>

